[1] Thailand, H5N1
Date: Thu, 2 Sep 2004
From: Alfonso Rodriguez <ajrm_msds@yahoo.es>
Source: Xinhuanet News, China, 2 Sep 2004 [edited]
<http://news3.xinhuanet.com/english/2004-09/02/content_1938798.htm>

Four more Thai provinces report bird flu outbreak
----------------------------------------------
4 more spots in Thailand have been confirmed of undergoing avian influenza
outbreak, the Agriculture Ministry said here on Thursday [2 Sep 2004].
The new outbreak was reported in 2 northern provinces and one central
province, the ministry's Department of Livestock Development said on its
website Thursday.[<http://www.dld.go.th/>, in Thai,no active English
version. - Mod.AS]
So far, some 29 areas in 14 provinces have been under the authorities'
monitoring for the reappeared bird flu, which first hit the kingdom in the
beginning of 2004, according to the website. The bird flu virus killed 8
people in Thailand and 16 in Vietnam during the 1st wave of the outbreak.
Thailand, which culled an estimated 50-60 million birds in the 1st round of
the epidemic, has come up with a series of measures to deal with the newly
reported outbreak.
Besides, a national committee set up to deal with the epidemic is expected
to come up with plans to overhaul the poultry industry by the end of
September 2004.
Thailand, the world's 4th largest poultry exporter, suffered a USD 880
million loss in the 1st wave of bird flu crisis, when major buyers such as
Japan and EU stopped imports from Thailand.
