[2] China, lifting restrictions
Date: Thu, 2 Sep 2004
From: Alfonso Rodriguez <ajrm_msds@yahoo.es>
Source: Yahoo News, Asia/China, 31 Aug 2004 [edited]
<http://asia.news.yahoo.com/040831/ap/d84q5v0g0.html>

China lifts ban on sale of poultry from province most recently affected by
bird flu
------------------------------------------------
China's quarantine authority has ended an export ban on poultry products
from eastern Anhui province imposed in July due to an outbreak of bird flu,
the government said Tuesday [31 Aug 2004].
China imposed the ban on 7 Jul 2004 to help prevent a repeat of a regional
epidemic of the H5N1 strain of bird flu that killed 27 people in Vietnam
and Thailand earlier in 2004 and cost producers in China and Southeast Asia
millions of dollars in losses from culled stocks.
Authorities killed more than 6000 birds after discovering the disease had
resurfaced in poultry in Anhui. Those efforts were successful in quelling
the disease, the official Xinhua News Agency said in announcing the end of
the export ban. However, it said local officials were cautioned to "do a
good job" in conducting quarantine checks.
International health officials have expressed concern over the disclosure
that 2 strains of bird flu, including the H5N1 strain, were found earlier
in 2004 in pigs in China. That finding, experts say, suggests that a more
dangerous, mutant virus could yet erupt in Asia.
